We did it! ✨✨✨

Back in September, as I transitioned out of my media company to run @myhappyflo full time, I downloaded an app called the gratitude jar. I am a believer that if you are grateful for the things that you have, more will come, so I was looking for a dope app that would help me record daily wins. Even if they were as small as getting up an hour earlier to write or run off to a Pilates class, I wanted to practice living my life feeling blessed and abundant. 

The more I sat in that space of gratitude each day, the more blessings seem to flow. So many things happened, and so quickly,, but One of the biggest blessings was snagging the grand prize of $25,000 in the @sheamoisture and @itsbrowngirljane #browngirlswap grant competition. 

Thank you so much for showing up for @myhappyflo.co and helping us win!  Every vote mattered!! Thank you to  Shea Moisture and Brown Girl Jane for recognizing small business owners and giving them the money and resources needed to flourish. I am so grateful!

Also, God bless y'all for tweeting and telling the world about My Happy Flo! (Swipe left to see some of my favorites) Thank you!!!! From the bottom of my heart! I see you! 

P.S. Buy you a bottle of My Happy Flo, and get that gratitude app. thank me later! 🙏🏽❤️

This is totally a Friday night photo dump, but I'm going to go off the rails for a minute...

I woke up this morning thinking about how for over 10+ years, I couldn't stay in one place. I was a city hopper, moving place to place and state to state while being plagued by what some would peg "destination addiction". It's the belief that happiness is everywhere but where you currently are, and so life becomes a constant uprooting and search for something that you'll eventually realize you have to find within you. 

I've been here in Atlanta for over 4 years while spending 3 of those years talking about how I was going to move soon 😂😂. And one day I woke up and realized that when you stay still for awhile, some magical things begin to happen. Instead of constant chaos and disarray, you become planted, and your seeds have the chance to blossom into beautiful flowers. You are able to finally get in alignment, and attract and manifest people who will change your life forever, as well as your deepest desires. It's believing, "God in this moment, where I am now, I trust you", instead of always feeling like what he has for you is somewhere you currently are not.

Sitting still in this season has been the best gift I've allowed myself to have and I've grown tremendously while meeting some incredibly amazing humans 

**steps off soapbox 

@imanibeautyau is one of those incredible humans! thank you for your friendship girrrrrrlllll!!! I love you!!!! You have been such a blessing over the last few years and one of the most amazing, genuine spirits that I know. Thank you for allowing us to celebrate you for your birthday! This was a hard thread to tweet but 3 weeks ago, I restarted therapy and I am learning to process grief in a way that I haven’t been able to before. My therapist is currently having me write goodbye letters to everyone who I am grieving.

I realized in this process that I’ve grieved many things — Heartbreaks, the death of my parents and grandparents, friendships ending. There's so many books, expert advice and IG pages dedicated to how to process those type of endings, but no one ever prepared me for the grief I would experience after selling and eventually walking away from a business.

The depression and anxiety over the last five years has been real, but I never felt I had a safe space to express this as someone who reached a goal so many entrepreneurs would have wanted to attain. Looking back, I definitely would have had a therapist and life coach on deck to help me to navigate various aspects of my transitions. 

This is what I do know for sure. If you have a business and you want to raise capital from investors, you have to accept that one day you may eventually sell your business (or go public). That is the way investors and VC funds make a return on their investment. You have to have an exit strategy and this isn't talked about a lot in the black community when it comes to conversations of how to start a business and how to raise money for that business. 

I tweeted this thread earlier this week, and I am sharing it here because being transparent and vulnerable about my experiences throughout my career has been a huge part of my healing journey. And the more I continue to process, the more I’ll continue to share insight around what I wish I knew throughout 15 years of building 3 brands ( the tax build up from the Necole Bitchie days is a whole other conversation.) I hope more black founders will share our experiences as we navigate the different stages of business (including fundraising, exits and acquisitions) and it will help others who are currently navigating the entrepreneurship space.

The Bible states, "He who finds a wife finds a good thing and obtains favor from the Lord." That means a woman becomes a wife before the vows. @hellonecole opened her heart to great vulnerability when she admitted never seeing herself valuable enough to be a wife.

When healthy love is triggering, you know you have some healing to do 👀

While binging watching love is blind this week and seeing how everything played out between some of the couples, it really reminded me of how self-sabotage shows up in dating relationships: Healthy love can be triggering to those who have not healed, and may cause you to choose someone less safe or a bit more chaotic because that's your comfort zone. I've been there. 

Also pattern changes happen in relationships no matter how healthy that relationship is. I had to learn to lean on my intuition and discernment, but also make sure I wasn't putting on my running shoes at the first sign of change if I wanted to be in a partnership for the long run. It required me to dig deep and ask, "Why is consistency giving me anxiety? Why is him showing up for me every day got me pulling and running?? It had more to do with me and my attachment style (which was a blend of anxious and avoidant) than it did the men I was dating. I'm transitioning into more of a secure attachment style but it has taken some time and also seeking out partners who've made me feel safe and secure as well as had open communication. 

I've unpacked so much through my dating experiences over the last few years and through a love that left me better versus bitter or broken. 

I am healing, I am worthy and I am so in love with the woman I am becoming 💕

Anyway, I had a good time talking to @laterrasrwhitfield from the @dearfuturewifeypodcast back in March. If you haven't already, Check it out on YouTube 😀

You look happier is one of the best compliments you can receive 💫 Healing girl summer playlist loading 😘

📸: @writeonkiah

Back in January, I remember leaving the person I was dating an emotional voice note telling him that I needed time. I had just switched manufacturers, was slapped with Nexus in several states, and it was tax season. Not to mention, I was extremely frustrated that no one warned me that running a product based business took this much work 😭. I was burned out, overworked, stressed, exhausted, had decision fatigue and on top of all that, trying to nurture a dating situation had me maxed out. I wasn't trying to run, I was just overwhelmed and lacked the capacity🥴 

I remember asking myself how long I was going to have to put work before actually living? This wasn't the life I signed up for. I wanted a refund lol. 

In February, I went into what I like to call my soft life era where I put more focus on my personal life, travel, adventure, new experiences and some much needed therapy, while working a lot less. With  several key automations in place, and minimizing the team a little, I was able to  reduce my 50+ hour work weeks to 10-15 hour. I was only going to do this for a month to recharge, but a strange thing happened: Revenue doubled 👀👀. After this happened for two months consistently with me working less, I took it as a sign from God that He wanted me to sit down for a minute, and also focus on some healing versus constantly using overworking and overachieving as a trauma response. 🙄

Soft life Necole lasted about 3 months and I feel so recharged, refreshed, rejuvenated, and have also unlocked the part of me that is more creative, more receiving, more in flow, and less feeling the need to control.  I love this life and deserve this life. 

It's time to get back to my purpose. I'd love to scale @myhappyflo into the life-changing brand I know it can be without sacrificing rest and too much of my life to do so. In this coming season, my calling means more to me than my comfort but there will be much more balance. 

It was fun, and I'll be back ☺️

Hello August 🌻

✨We're Going Live Tonight!!✨ Imagine having a traumatizing period at the age of 12, and realizing this could be your new norm every month for the next 30 years of life.  This was @inkverywell’s story as no one had ever prepared her for a lifetime of periods that included vomiting, bleeding through layers of clothing, intense cramping and having to rely on 6 Ibuprofen multiple times a day. 

After trying teas, yoni steams, plant based and vegan diets, as well as multiple forms of birth control that would result in her having what she pegs “Revenge Periods,” INK J was gifted two bottles of My Happy Flo from her sister who didn’t want to see her suffer anymore as she awaited a surgery to remove fibroids and cysts.  Not only did she experience what she likes to call “the most non-tormented period” in her life, a few months later, when it was time for her surgery, she was notified by her doctors that they could no longer find the fibroids!   Since then, her periods are now an average of 3-5 days, with minimal to no symptoms, and she feels as though she’s finally got her life back! 

Join us on IG Live tonight @ 8pm as @inkverywell shares her inspiring story with @hellonecole. She will reveal how long she was on @myhappyflo before her scheduled surgery as well as other life-changing shifts she's experienced since implementing the vitamins into her daily routine. She also has a word of caution for those who may have upcoming fibroid surgeries about giving consent to remove vital organs that could result in an unplanned full hysterectomy.

If you have any questions for @inkverywell, drop them in the comments 👇🏾

The year was 2012.  January 7 to be exact and I was sitting on a blind date in West Hollywood that a few friends had set me up on. The conversation was going great when a text came in from a friend who was well-connected in the industry. Beyoncé had her baby and news would hit soon but she wanted me to be one of the first to know. 

Being a blogger at the time, and hungry to be the first to break any news that came my way, I had to make a decision on whether I'd sit through another hour of a date with a potentially good match for me, or would I scurry out of there so I can be on top of the juicy entail. 

Spoiler alert: I scurried out of there and that was the last of that date. It took me a long time to forgive Bey 🤣 The next year she dropped a surprise album while I was at a holiday party and that was part 2 of me scurrying out of a moment. 

It's 11 years later, and I can't begin to express  the emotions of watching the little star that is Blue Ivy performing with her mom on stage. Such a reminder of the preciousness of time, living in the moment, and seeing dreams manifest. The way Bey looks at Blue, you can tell she's so proud 😇

This was the first concert I've been to in a long time, and I was able to enjoy it as a fan with no expectations or obligations. I struggled with whether to post this clip today considering... 

Promising myself I'd enjoy many many more concerts to come❤️🙏🏽

One of the prettiest cakes I've ever seen. 😍 Growing up I used to go to birthday parties for the kids in my class but I always wondered why I wasn't celebrated in the same way.  My birthday would come, but it wouldn't include balloons, party invites, gifts and cake. 

Later in life, I realized it was because my mom probably couldn't afford to, wasn't into celebrations like that, or maybe overwhelmed by the thought of planning. It takes a village. 

At any rate, it resulted in me growing up an overachiever bundled with perfectionist and wanting to do something worthy of one day getting recognition and a celebration. I went throughout adulthood, still not having parties except for that one year two record label VP's Michael Kyser and Joie Manda got together and threw me this huge party in New York. I flew in from Atlanta to a packed out venue complete with celebs and the world famous @dnice as the DJ. All I had to do was show up! 

I'll never forget them doing that for me.  They didn't know that was my first party ever.  About seven years later @latoyashambo and @mskamille would put together this party for me in New York for the launch of xoNecole with the most beautiful cakes on the desert table. 

Fast forward to today, and cake has become a big deal for me. It symbolizes to me being worthy of celebrating and all the good things life has to offer. 🥂 So this year, when my friends surprised me with a custom cake during my birthday dinner, it was one of the best birthday surprises I could have received. 

@cakedbypetite is black woman owned by the way and the cakes don't just look good, they taste good too. 

Thank you again friend @writeonkiah 

P.s. I order cake every chance I get when eating out now. Moral of the story: Eat the cake! Celebrate yourself 

#atlantabirthday #atlantabirthdaycakes #cakedbypetite @littleburger joiemanda

A year ago, I was faced with the challenge of growing an e-comm brand but running out of money fast due to inventory demands. As a business under 2 years old, it was hard to qualify for bank loans and when funding was offered, it was at predatory interest rates that would keep my business under water. 

@fearless.fund was one of the first VC funds to not only show interest in providing capital to @myhappyflo but they also awarded us funding of about $30-40k in the form of various grants throughout the year. That funding came at a very crucial stage and the reason my brand is still in business.  Fearless fund also hosts accelerator programs to help black businesses get venture ready and during their pitch contests each year, they award over $250k to black women owned businesses 

We all know the stats that less than .34% in vc funding goes to black Women and although we make up 42% of new businesses formed, access to capital to grow and scale those businesses are just not as readily available. That's why when I heard that the fund was being named in an affirmative action suit  for providing grants to women of color, I was a bit shocked.  They are being sued for racial discrimination for providing grants to women of color! 😳

I stand with fearless fund and I hope you do too. Visit fearlessfreedomnow.org to donate, sign the petition and let you voice be heard. With our support, we can help them win this suit and continue to provide access and the resources we women of color need to thrive, grow and sustain their businesses. ✨

**tap the link in my bio to learn more 

#fearlessfreedom #fearlessfund #fearlessfreedomnow #takeaction

It's been a long time since I've been in college, so when I received the call that I had been accepted into a business program for entrepreneurs at one of the most elite colleges in the nation, of course my anxiety flared up real bad.
